WEBVTT

00:14.896 --> 00:17.000
- Shh.
[horse snorts]

00:18.931 --> 00:21.862
[softly] Shh. Yeah.

00:21.965 --> 00:23.793
Yeah.

00:23.896 --> 00:26.862
Yeah, easy. Easy.

00:26.965 --> 00:29.310
[low whinny]

00:29.413 --> 00:30.586
Oh.

00:33.241 --> 00:34.310
It's not fair, this life.

00:38.517 --> 00:40.896
[grunts]

00:41.000 --> 00:43.586
- I know you deserve better.

00:45.517 --> 00:46.655
[cocks trigger]

00:48.103 --> 00:50.344
Best I can offer you
is peace.

00:51.965 --> 00:54.862
[cows lowing]

00:54.965 --> 00:57.551
[somber music]

00:57.655 --> 01:05.586
♪

01:19.068 --> 01:20.551
[metallic clatter]

01:31.172 --> 01:32.862
[steam hissing]

01:41.758 --> 01:47.206
[indistinct radio chatter]

01:50.931 --> 01:52.241
[radio chatter]

02:03.862 --> 02:08.378
[sirens wailing]

02:08.482 --> 02:12.482
[somber music continues]

02:12.586 --> 02:19.517
♪

02:19.620 --> 02:23.758
[sirens wailing]

02:28.896 --> 02:32.586
[cows lowing]

02:39.310 --> 02:40.793
[brakes screech]

02:40.896 --> 02:42.482
[car doors shut]

02:42.586 --> 02:45.655
The things we lose
to keep you fed.

02:45.758 --> 02:46.827
[lowing]

02:46.931 --> 02:49.724
[police radio chatter]

02:49.827 --> 02:51.034
- Jesus, that's John Dutton.

02:51.137 --> 02:53.655
Commissioner, you all right?

02:57.137 --> 02:59.827
[dramatic music]

02:59.931 --> 03:07.241
♪

03:59.206 --> 04:01.586
[indistinct chatter]

04:01.689 --> 04:05.586
- The state of Montana
has never gauged its progress

04:05.689 --> 04:08.793
by the size of its cities.

04:08.896 --> 04:10.517
We measure our progress

04:10.620 --> 04:13.000
by how those cities
impact the people

04:13.103 --> 04:14.137
and the land surrounding them,

04:14.241 --> 04:16.896
the land that feeds them,

04:17.000 --> 04:20.482
provides their water,
nourishes their souls.

04:20.586 --> 04:22.482
- This doesn't sound like
a legal argument, Mr. Dutton.

04:22.586 --> 04:24.482
It sounds like a lecture.

04:24.586 --> 04:26.551
- Well, it's a summation
of our state constitution,

04:26.655 --> 04:28.103
which clearly states
that land preservation

04:28.206 --> 04:30.068
and property rights
take precedence

04:30.172 --> 04:31.655
over public expansion.

04:31.758 --> 04:33.724
- The constitution
clearly denotes

04:33.827 --> 04:35.448
the state's right
to eminent domain

04:35.551 --> 04:37.172
and grants the authority
to condemn property

04:37.275 --> 04:38.724
for the public good.

04:38.827 --> 04:39.689
- For essential
public services

04:39.793 --> 04:42.448
like hospitals, schools,
highways--

04:42.551 --> 04:44.068
not housing developments.

04:44.172 --> 04:46.655
- Housing is essential.

04:46.758 --> 04:49.310
Bozeman has doubled
in size in a decade.

04:49.413 --> 04:51.310
We're 30 miles away,

04:51.413 --> 04:55.310
and our population is less
than it was 40 years ago.

04:55.413 --> 04:59.931
Why? Because their fence
guarantees we don't grow.

05:00.034 --> 05:01.482
Stagnation is death for a town,

05:01.586 --> 05:03.689
and the Duttons
are the ones killing it.

05:03.793 --> 05:06.413
- Well, poetic if it were true,

05:06.517 --> 05:08.827
since a Dutton
founded the town.

05:08.931 --> 05:11.275
As it stands,
the defendant is correct.

05:11.379 --> 05:13.931
Our land use laws
are quite clear.

05:14.034 --> 05:15.793
For this commission
to grant eminent domain,

05:15.896 --> 05:20.137
you must show
public need, not desire.

05:20.241 --> 05:21.689
- I think
that's enough posturing.

05:21.793 --> 05:23.379
Let's put it to a vote.
- The plaintiff hasn't shown

05:23.482 --> 05:25.137
any legal imperative
for a vote,

05:25.241 --> 05:27.137
so this case is dismissed.

05:27.241 --> 05:28.448
[gavel thuds]

05:31.379 --> 05:34.586
- It's 30,000 acres, Jamie.

05:34.689 --> 05:37.344
That isn't a fraction
of the ranch.

05:37.448 --> 05:40.689
Okay, look, you can harvest
the timber first,

05:40.793 --> 05:42.344
no environmental review,
nothing.

05:42.448 --> 05:46.344
You can cut every tree
to the root.

05:46.448 --> 05:47.896
- You want to suggest
to my father

05:48.000 --> 05:49.137
that he clear-cut his land,
be my guest.

05:49.241 --> 05:51.103
You're a braver man than me.

05:51.206 --> 05:54.275
- Just mention it, Jamie.

05:54.379 --> 05:55.448
The town grows, or it dies.

05:55.551 --> 05:57.758
- Well, maybe it
should grow...up.

05:57.862 --> 06:01.862
Condos, Alan, like
they have in San Francisco.

06:01.965 --> 06:04.896
- Condos?

06:05.000 --> 06:07.793
Who wants to live
in a condo in Montana?

06:20.103 --> 06:22.758
- I don't know how you're gonna
get 'em out by yourself.

06:22.862 --> 06:24.724
- Don't have to get 'em
all out.

06:25.448 --> 06:27.758
Just that stallion.

06:27.862 --> 06:30.241
Once he's gone, the rest
will leave on their own.

06:30.344 --> 06:32.965
- Best of luck. That bastard
kicked my truck door so hard,

06:33.068 --> 06:35.034
we had to use a crowbar
to get it open.

06:35.137 --> 06:38.413
That damn mustang's done more
in one week to stop drilling

06:38.517 --> 06:40.620
than every environmental
group in the state.

06:40.724 --> 06:43.551
- Maybe I should just leave him
where he is then.

06:46.206 --> 06:48.379
- Where'd you find this guy?

06:48.482 --> 06:50.448
- Yellow pages.

06:50.551 --> 06:52.551
Ad says he works
with problem horses.

06:52.655 --> 06:54.448
- Oh, this'll be interesting.

06:56.689 --> 06:57.931
- Kid's fucking crazy.

06:59.103 --> 07:01.034
[horse whinnies]

07:02.241 --> 07:05.379
- Yeah, uh...

07:05.482 --> 07:07.793
sure is building something.

07:09.551 --> 07:10.827
[knock on door]

07:10.931 --> 07:13.000
- [softly] Beth.
- Of course he didn't.

07:13.103 --> 07:15.000
He couldn't find his ass
with both hands.

07:15.103 --> 07:16.931
- Bob--Bob needs you.
- Give me a minute.

07:17.034 --> 07:19.965
- I don't think
he has a minute.

07:20.068 --> 07:21.724
- God damn it, Bob,
I didn't come here

07:21.827 --> 07:23.482
to do business
with these people.

07:23.586 --> 07:25.137
I came here to do
business with you.

07:25.241 --> 07:29.103
- I can hear you screaming
halfway down the hall, Craig.

07:34.241 --> 07:36.551
- I thought we were gonna try
and work this out, Bob.

07:36.655 --> 07:38.000
- We've been trying
to work this out

07:38.103 --> 07:40.655
for three hours, Craig.

07:40.758 --> 07:42.620
This is the alternative.

07:42.724 --> 07:43.965
- We don't want to merge.

07:44.068 --> 07:45.965
- No one wants
to merge with you.

07:46.068 --> 07:47.551
You have
a three-to-one debt ratio.

07:47.655 --> 07:50.275
It'd be easier to sell VCRs.

07:50.379 --> 07:54.275
- I'm not gonna be bullied
by your hatchet man, Bob.

07:54.379 --> 07:55.931
We will pull our funds,

07:56.034 --> 07:59.931
and we will take our business
down the street to Chase.

08:00.034 --> 08:02.172
- We're just asking you
to suspend the dividend.

08:02.275 --> 08:03.172
- And kill the stock!

08:03.275 --> 08:05.068
- What do you think's
gonna happen

08:05.172 --> 08:08.344
when I dump our 18% share
tomorrow morning?

08:08.448 --> 08:09.655
I'll tell you what.

08:09.758 --> 08:11.586
The stock will drop below 10,

08:11.689 --> 08:12.862
SEC will suspend trading,

08:12.965 --> 08:15.862
and every creditor you have
will file on you.

08:15.965 --> 08:19.724
Your company will be
chapter 11 by Friday,

08:19.827 --> 08:21.862
and since we're
your largest creditors,

08:21.965 --> 08:25.034
I can promise you there'll be
no negotiating then.

08:25.137 --> 08:28.620
I will be CEO of
IL Energy by Monday.

08:28.724 --> 08:30.034
I will fire every
fucking employee.

08:30.137 --> 08:33.827
Then I will sell your leases
and equipment to Chevron

08:33.931 --> 08:36.724
for 30¢ on the dollar,
and you, buddy,

08:36.827 --> 08:39.724
you will have
the unique distinction

08:39.827 --> 08:40.827
of being the only
drilling company

08:40.931 --> 08:44.034
to go bankrupt
in the largest oil boom

08:44.136 --> 08:46.448
of the last century.

08:46.551 --> 08:49.689
Won't that look good
on a resume?

08:49.793 --> 08:53.655
- I started this company
in my garage.

08:53.758 --> 08:55.310
- That's where
it's gonna end up

08:55.413 --> 08:56.344
if you don't suspend
the dividend

08:56.448 --> 08:58.758
and allow us
to assume management.

09:00.758 --> 09:02.758
Don't look at him.

09:02.862 --> 09:05.000
You're dealing with me now.

09:06.758 --> 09:09.137
So what's it gonna be?

09:09.241 --> 09:12.000
Are we restructuring
your company tomorrow

09:12.103 --> 09:13.344
or killing it?

09:18.310 --> 09:19.620
- Good.

09:19.724 --> 09:22.241
You made the right choice,
Craig.

09:26.931 --> 09:27.965
We'll get you through this.

09:32.931 --> 09:34.724
- [under breath] Bitch.

09:40.517 --> 09:42.689
- I just saved your house.

09:42.793 --> 09:45.068
I put your kids
through college.

09:45.172 --> 09:48.620
Maybe you should say
something more appropriate.

09:52.724 --> 09:54.068
- Thank you.

09:55.448 --> 09:57.241
- You're welcome.

10:03.137 --> 10:03.517
[horse whinnies]

10:03.620 --> 10:05.241
[thump]

10:07.413 --> 10:10.413
[horse whinnying, thrashing]

10:10.517 --> 10:12.172
[muffled thumping]

10:12.275 --> 10:13.758
[horse whinnying]

10:13.862 --> 10:16.517
[thudding continues]

10:16.620 --> 10:19.896
[pop/folksy rap music]

10:20.000 --> 10:26.103
♪

10:26.206 --> 10:29.448
[rapping]

10:29.551 --> 10:31.793
[horse whinnies]
[thump]

10:31.896 --> 10:34.482
- ♪ Another suicide,
that's just the worst ♪

10:34.586 --> 10:37.379
[indistinct singing]

10:37.482 --> 10:39.482
♪

10:39.586 --> 10:41.862
[horse whinnies]
[thump]

10:41.965 --> 10:44.068
♪ And here's the kinda town

10:44.172 --> 10:48.275
♪ Singing to the moon
our lonesome song ♪

10:48.379 --> 10:52.862
[horse continues
whinnying]

10:52.965 --> 10:54.482
[thump]

10:54.586 --> 11:00.000
[song continues]
[thumping continues]

11:00.103 --> 11:01.896
[horse snorts]

11:02.000 --> 11:04.241
[horse whinnying,
thrashing]

11:04.344 --> 11:07.551
[thumping, snorting]

11:07.655 --> 11:09.965
[children playing]
[thumping continues]

11:10.068 --> 11:11.206
- Daddy!

11:11.310 --> 11:12.827
- Hey, buddy.

11:12.931 --> 11:15.344
[horse continues thumping,
whinnying]

11:16.965 --> 11:18.758
- Bet it was fun putting him
in the trailer.

11:18.862 --> 11:21.206
- Yeah, they call him
a tornado.

11:21.310 --> 11:22.896
- How are you planning
on getting him out?

11:23.000 --> 11:25.517
- I'm just making this up
as I go, babe.

11:25.620 --> 11:28.000
[thumping, snorting
continues]

11:28.103 --> 11:29.620
I'd step back a bit further
if I were you.

11:29.724 --> 11:33.379
[horse whinnying,
thumping]

11:33.482 --> 11:35.310
It's all right.

11:35.413 --> 11:36.551
[thud]

11:36.655 --> 11:38.551
I know it don't
seem like it, but it is.

11:38.655 --> 11:41.758
[thudding, whinnying]

11:41.862 --> 11:43.517
Easy.
[horse snorting]

11:43.620 --> 11:45.758
Easy.
[horse grunts]

11:45.862 --> 11:48.000
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

11:48.103 --> 11:50.241
Easy, easy.
That's it.

11:50.344 --> 11:51.724
That's it.

11:53.482 --> 11:54.862
Hey.
[horse grunting, snorting]

11:55.965 --> 11:57.655
Whoa...whoa.
[horse grunting]

11:57.758 --> 11:58.413
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

11:58.517 --> 12:00.448
You kids get back!

12:00.551 --> 12:02.586
Hey, hey, hey.

12:02.689 --> 12:03.689
[grunting]

12:03.793 --> 12:06.793
That's it, that's it.
Come on.

12:06.896 --> 12:08.586
[horse grunting, snorting]

12:08.689 --> 12:10.448
It's all right.
It's all right.

12:10.551 --> 12:10.931
[horse grunting softer]

12:15.896 --> 12:17.413
- Can I pet him?

12:17.517 --> 12:19.034
- Sure, son,
in about a year.

12:19.137 --> 12:22.034
- No fear in this one.
He got that from you.

12:22.137 --> 12:25.413
- You mean no common sense.
He got that from you.

12:25.517 --> 12:31.448
- Well, I suppose your homework
is in the kitchen doing itself.

12:33.206 --> 12:34.758
[kids chattering,
giggling]

12:34.862 --> 12:36.103
[loud grunting]

12:36.206 --> 12:39.000
Oh, he's gonna be fun to break.

12:40.379 --> 12:43.310
Well, holler at me
if you need my help.

12:44.482 --> 12:46.206
- Free tomorrow?

12:46.310 --> 12:47.758
Could use a hand.

12:47.862 --> 12:49.758
- Yeah, sure.

12:49.862 --> 12:52.206
- Bring a horse.

12:52.310 --> 12:53.517
Just not that one.

12:59.344 --> 13:01.586
- Wow. My brother
actually talked to me.

13:01.689 --> 13:04.827
Well, that was progress.

13:04.931 --> 13:06.931
- Yeah, it was something.

13:07.034 --> 13:09.034
- I got parent conferences
tonight,

13:09.137 --> 13:11.137
so you're on Tate patrol.

13:11.241 --> 13:12.172
- All right.

13:14.896 --> 13:16.793
- I wonder what he's thinking.

13:17.724 --> 13:20.413
- Well, he's probably thinking
I took his freedom.

13:20.517 --> 13:21.586
- Well, he's right.

13:21.689 --> 13:24.793
[horse snuffling softly]

13:24.896 --> 13:26.275
Supper's ready.

13:40.965 --> 13:42.862
- Ah, damn it.

13:44.448 --> 13:48.000
Your mother was always
better at this.

13:49.137 --> 13:51.137
- Hey, you know
who's really good at it?

13:52.689 --> 13:54.000
Doctors.
- Yeah.

13:54.103 --> 13:57.103
- Should have done
that yesterday.

13:57.206 --> 14:00.103
Here, let me do it.
Let me do it.

14:02.068 --> 14:05.034
All right, Alan asked me
to mention it, so I will.

14:05.137 --> 14:07.551
They'd allow us to harvest
the timber before the--

14:07.655 --> 14:09.000
- No.

14:10.000 --> 14:11.448
The answer's no.
- Yeah.

14:11.551 --> 14:14.517
Can I do this?

14:14.620 --> 14:16.586
- Yeah.

14:16.689 --> 14:19.793
When you say no, it must be
the death of the question.

14:19.896 --> 14:21.000
- Mm-hmm, I understand.

14:21.103 --> 14:22.758
- If there's even a hint
of maybe,

14:22.862 --> 14:24.000
the questions won't stop
until they find

14:24.103 --> 14:25.551
something you can't say no to.

14:25.655 --> 14:26.206
- Mm.

14:31.689 --> 14:32.448
- You got to learn
when to think

14:32.551 --> 14:33.896
like a lawyer,
you understand?

14:34.000 --> 14:36.103
And when to think
like a landowner.

14:36.206 --> 14:38.344
Or a lawyer's
all you're ever gonna be.

14:41.413 --> 14:43.034
Yeah.

14:43.137 --> 14:45.862
Well, I'll say this.
You...

14:45.965 --> 14:47.206
You got your mother's hands.

14:50.413 --> 14:51.689
[barking]

14:51.793 --> 14:54.862
[helicopter blades whirring]

14:54.965 --> 14:58.344
[horses whinnying]

14:58.448 --> 14:59.862
- Hey.

14:59.965 --> 15:01.551
I told them no.

15:07.551 --> 15:09.655
Hey, I said
you wouldn't consider it.

15:10.793 --> 15:13.275
Should you consider it?
Absolutely.

15:15.275 --> 15:18.103
We could use the money and the
leverage that comes with it.

15:18.206 --> 15:19.655
- You're not coming, Dad?

15:21.137 --> 15:24.275
- No, I got a meeting
in Bozeman.

15:25.551 --> 15:28.793
Why don't you take
your badge out with you today?

15:28.896 --> 15:30.517
Take a rifle too.

15:30.620 --> 15:32.517
- I mean, they won't give us
any trouble over strays.

15:32.620 --> 15:34.344
I mean, hell, they'll probably
help us round them up.

15:34.448 --> 15:37.172
- Well, the badge is for
the ranchers riding with you.

15:37.275 --> 15:39.517
It'll keep them from
bringing home any extras.

15:41.758 --> 15:43.172
- Did you hear me?

15:43.275 --> 15:47.275
[helicopter engine
powering up thrum]

15:49.482 --> 15:52.275
- Leverage is knowing
if someone had...

15:52.379 --> 15:54.206
all the money in the world...

15:56.586 --> 15:59.034
This is what they'd buy.

15:59.137 --> 16:02.275
[foreboding music]

16:02.379 --> 16:09.241
♪

16:22.793 --> 16:26.344
[intense music build-up]

16:31.034 --> 16:33.931
[soft, dramatic music]

16:34.034 --> 16:39.137
♪

16:39.241 --> 16:41.655
[bird of prey cries]

16:41.758 --> 16:44.206
[distant chanting]

16:44.310 --> 16:46.448
[chanting in native language]

16:46.551 --> 16:49.655
♪

16:49.758 --> 16:53.275
[drumming intensifies]

16:53.379 --> 16:55.965
[chanting]

16:56.068 --> 17:02.275
♪

17:07.378 --> 17:09.550
[chanting, drumming continue]

17:09.655 --> 17:11.310
[knocking at door]

17:11.413 --> 17:14.310
[chanting and drumming
continues in background]

17:17.862 --> 17:18.931
- Senator.

17:19.034 --> 17:21.275
- I'm sorry I'm late.

17:21.378 --> 17:23.586
I wanted to see
the reservation first.

17:23.689 --> 17:25.068
- Did you enjoy your tour?

17:25.172 --> 17:27.275
- No, no, I did not.

17:27.378 --> 17:29.896
- Well, it's good
that you took it.

17:30.000 --> 17:31.793
Inequity must be witnessed
to be changed.

17:31.896 --> 17:33.586
Please have a seat.

17:33.689 --> 17:35.241
- Oh.

17:37.655 --> 17:38.827
I can't imagine all
your mother overcame

17:38.931 --> 17:40.379
just to raise you here.

17:40.482 --> 17:44.551
- I never met my mother,
and I wasn't raised here.

17:44.655 --> 17:47.137
Till I was 18,
I thought I was Mexican

17:47.241 --> 17:49.241
even though
I didn't look Mexican

17:49.344 --> 17:51.206
and I didn't feel Mexican,

17:51.310 --> 17:53.482
if one can feel their heritage,
which I believe one can.

17:53.586 --> 17:58.137
When I turned 18, my adoption
records were unsealed,

17:58.241 --> 18:00.827
and imagine my surprise.

18:00.931 --> 18:03.000
I confronted
my adopted parents,

18:03.103 --> 18:05.310
who said they lied
to protect me.

18:07.034 --> 18:10.137
They said as a Mexican,

18:10.241 --> 18:13.241
I would face
discrimination, sure,

18:13.344 --> 18:17.655
but as an Indian,
I would know a hatred

18:17.758 --> 18:21.448
that had to be endured
to be fully understood.

18:21.551 --> 18:25.000
They thought they were giving
me a better chance at life.

18:25.103 --> 18:30.379
That's this nation's policy
toward us, always has been.

18:30.482 --> 18:33.344
If we want a better life,
all we have to do

18:33.448 --> 18:35.482
is stop being Indian.

18:35.586 --> 18:37.689
- I'm gonna change that policy.

18:37.793 --> 18:41.379
- My people are the only ones
that can change that policy.

18:43.517 --> 18:45.275
[sighs]

18:45.379 --> 18:47.482
The gambler's money
is like a river,

18:47.586 --> 18:51.931
flowing one way...
our way.

18:52.034 --> 18:53.413
Senator, you've
never driven a road

18:53.517 --> 18:57.517
or walked a trail
or skied a mountain in Montana

18:57.620 --> 19:00.275
that didn't belong
to my people first.

19:00.379 --> 19:04.000
This nation doesn't
want to give it back?

19:04.103 --> 19:04.931
So be it.

19:05.034 --> 19:07.758
We'll buy it back...

19:07.862 --> 19:10.241
with their money.

19:10.344 --> 19:11.344
- So what do you want from me?

19:14.482 --> 19:16.793
- I want you to help me
spend it.

19:18.241 --> 19:20.482
Come. Meet the people
we're saving.

19:24.000 --> 19:27.689
- Ladies and gentlemen,
let's welcome the new chairman

19:27.793 --> 19:30.931
of Broken Rock,
Thomas Rainwater!

19:31.034 --> 19:34.862
[cheers and applause]

19:39.000 --> 19:40.482
- What about water and power?

19:40.586 --> 19:42.793
You don't need
a permit for that?

19:42.896 --> 19:45.724
See, the bank's concern is
that you're gonna break ground,

19:45.827 --> 19:49.310
and the state or the fucking
EPA paper us in lawsuits

19:49.413 --> 19:51.586
because we built a power plant
without a permit.

19:51.689 --> 19:54.482
- In the state of Montana,
no permit is required

19:54.586 --> 19:57.482
to build a power source
for a mine or a mill.

19:57.586 --> 19:59.758
Now, we'll construct
our own mill

19:59.862 --> 20:00.931
that will also allow us
to harvest wood

20:01.034 --> 20:04.862
directly from the forest,

20:04.965 --> 20:07.793
cutting our lumber cost by 65%.

20:10.344 --> 20:13.275
Damming the river here
will generate enough power

20:13.379 --> 20:15.172
to light every home
in the subdivision.

20:15.275 --> 20:17.827
Now, this is a self-sustaining
community

20:17.931 --> 20:23.172
30 miles from the most pristine
wilderness in North America.

20:23.275 --> 20:25.379
Now, if you don't see
the potential in that,

20:25.482 --> 20:27.965
we need another bank.
- We see the potential.

20:28.068 --> 20:29.310
I just--

20:29.413 --> 20:32.275
There are no restrictions
on damming a river?

20:32.379 --> 20:35.241
- Beavers do it
all the time.

20:35.344 --> 20:38.034
On our land it's our river.

20:38.137 --> 20:40.241
Now, this isn't California,
gentlemen.

20:40.344 --> 20:41.413
This is Montana.

20:45.310 --> 20:47.827
We can do whatever we want.

20:48.448 --> 20:52.724
[traffic noises]

20:52.827 --> 20:54.724
[soft rock playing]

20:54.827 --> 21:02.758
♪

21:14.448 --> 21:17.586
- My name's Ted.
Where are you from?

21:19.965 --> 21:21.413
Really?
[laughs]

21:21.517 --> 21:23.103
I've been here a week.

21:23.206 --> 21:26.068
You're the first person I've
met who's actually from here.

21:26.172 --> 21:28.551
Can I buy you another drink?

21:28.655 --> 21:29.862
- Why not?

21:31.137 --> 21:33.413
Hey, Dalton,
give me another one.

21:33.517 --> 21:34.724
- You don't live here anymore,
though, not dressed like that.

21:35.655 --> 21:39.448
You came back
for a family reunion.

21:39.551 --> 21:43.241
No, no, those never happen
at home for some reason.

21:43.344 --> 21:47.310
Let's see, Bozeman
is a college town,

21:47.413 --> 21:51.000
so I'm gonna say
a school reunion,

21:51.103 --> 21:54.758
class of...2006.

21:56.068 --> 21:58.793
Am I close?

21:58.896 --> 22:00.344
- Do you feel close, Ted?

22:00.448 --> 22:02.896
- Ah, it feels like
I'm getting close.

22:03.000 --> 22:05.344
- My turn.

22:07.103 --> 22:07.896
You're in real estate
or something

22:08.000 --> 22:10.379
equally as unimportant,
married,

22:10.482 --> 22:12.103
couple of kids, one on the way.

22:12.206 --> 22:14.551
That was your excuse
to come out here.

22:14.655 --> 22:16.827
Need the break.
Work, family life.

22:16.931 --> 22:17.862
It's so demanding.

22:17.965 --> 22:20.758
A little fresh air,
a little "me time."

22:20.862 --> 22:23.862
You came alone 'cause none of
your friends could afford it,

22:23.965 --> 22:25.586
and those who do,
they--they have wives

22:25.689 --> 22:27.482
a lot smarter than yours
'cause let's be honest, Ted,

22:27.586 --> 22:28.965
you didn't come here to fish.

22:29.068 --> 22:31.310
You're hunting.

22:31.413 --> 22:32.551
That's why
you're sitting in a bar

22:32.655 --> 22:35.068
instead of standing in a river.

22:36.241 --> 22:37.896
- Who the hell are you
to judge me?

22:38.000 --> 22:39.793
- I ain't judging you, buddy.

22:39.896 --> 22:41.275
- Morning, gentlemen.

22:41.379 --> 22:45.103
- I'm hunting too,
just not hunting you.

22:45.206 --> 22:47.413
- What's wrong with me?

22:48.379 --> 22:51.482
- You look like
a real soft fuck, Ted.

22:51.586 --> 22:53.931
All you city boys do.

22:58.655 --> 23:01.310
Gentlemen,
mind if I join you?

23:01.413 --> 23:03.379
[men shouting]

23:03.482 --> 23:05.379
- They even got
the barb wire tore down.

23:06.413 --> 23:07.517
That is our property,
god damn it.

23:07.620 --> 23:11.551
- Can't hear ya.
Come about 2 feet closer.

23:11.655 --> 23:14.034
- You think I won't?
- I think you shouldn't,

23:14.137 --> 23:17.068
but coming on our land
is bred into you people.

23:17.172 --> 23:19.137
- I've had enough of your shit.

23:20.275 --> 23:20.586
Let me tell you something--

23:22.275 --> 23:24.655
[men shouting]

23:24.758 --> 23:26.413
- When those cattle
walked onto our land,

23:26.517 --> 23:29.379
they became our cattle
to do as we please.

23:29.482 --> 23:32.172
- Whatever happens next
happens to you first.

23:32.275 --> 23:35.172
[helicopter whirring]

23:35.275 --> 23:36.517
[tense music]

23:36.620 --> 23:38.172
- Son of a bitch.

23:38.275 --> 23:42.241
♪

23:42.344 --> 23:43.586
- Back up.

23:43.689 --> 23:45.827
- You should respect
your veterans.

24:03.689 --> 24:05.517
- Boy, you sure made
a mess of this.

24:05.620 --> 24:08.000
- It was a mess
when I got here.

24:09.379 --> 24:10.758
- This is a tribal issue, John.

24:10.862 --> 24:12.655
Livestock commission's
got no authority here.

24:12.758 --> 24:14.965
- Those look like livestock
to me.

24:16.103 --> 24:19.724
- The Chief's at Commencement,
but I'm calling the shots.

24:21.137 --> 24:24.034
- I'm impressed you said that
with a straight face, Ben.

24:28.586 --> 24:31.551
- Cattle wandered
onto res land, John.

24:31.655 --> 24:33.379
- Yeah, well,

24:33.482 --> 24:34.241
cattle don't know
the difference

24:34.344 --> 24:35.931
between your land and ours.

24:36.034 --> 24:37.620
- Neither did we
till the government

24:37.724 --> 24:38.551
showed us.
Ha.

24:38.655 --> 24:41.724
Now I guess we're showing you.

24:43.068 --> 24:45.758
I argued against it,
but the new chief...

24:48.206 --> 24:50.137
Hungry for a fight, this one.

24:50.241 --> 24:52.206
- God damn it, I just--

24:53.724 --> 24:56.827
I just don't see how anyone
gains from all this, Felix.

24:56.931 --> 25:00.275
- I don't either,
but he don't think like me.

25:01.413 --> 25:02.275
Grew up in Denver,

25:02.379 --> 25:06.551
went to some big university.

25:06.655 --> 25:07.758
Now he thinks like you.

25:18.137 --> 25:20.827
I'll keep 'em here
as long as I can, John.

25:24.137 --> 25:25.758
- I'll bring up hay
so they don't wander.

25:29.448 --> 25:32.655
Lee!
- I got to go.

25:33.827 --> 25:34.689
- Clear everyone out.

25:37.379 --> 25:40.103
- You know, there was barbed
wire on this fence a week ago.

25:42.965 --> 25:44.931
- I know.
Now clear them out.

25:45.034 --> 25:47.896
- Move out!
All right, let's go!

25:48.000 --> 25:50.758
- ♪ Our flag was still there

25:50.862 --> 25:57.413
♪ Oh, say does that
star-spangled ♪

25:57.517 --> 26:03.448
♪ Banner yet wave

26:03.551 --> 26:08.724
♪ O'er the land of the free

26:08.827 --> 26:15.344
♪ And the home
of the brave ♪

26:15.448 --> 26:19.241
[cheers and applause]

26:22.517 --> 26:24.310
- Ladies and gentlemen,
I'd like to welcome you out

26:24.413 --> 26:25.931
to the 2018

26:26.034 --> 26:28.000
Greater Montana
Livestock Auction.

26:28.103 --> 26:29.689
We're gonna start out
with lot number one.

26:29.793 --> 26:32.758
It's Royal M. Duke,
a 2013 registered

26:32.862 --> 26:35.655
English bull offered
by Double G Angus Ranch,

26:35.758 --> 26:39.000
sired by Supreme Domino
out of Miss Domino.

26:39.103 --> 26:40.827
Now we're gonna start
the bidding out at 25,000.

26:40.931 --> 26:44.862
I'm at 25. I'm at 50.
[auctioneering]

26:44.965 --> 26:45.827
I'm at 55, gonna go 60,
at 60 now,

26:45.931 --> 26:49.379
now 5 on 65,000,
65 looking for 70.

26:49.482 --> 26:51.310
[auctioneering] 75, 75

26:51.413 --> 26:53.034
and now bid
at 80, 80,000, 85?

26:53.137 --> 26:54.482
85, now 90, 90?

26:54.586 --> 26:56.931
- One phone call.
I'll be right back.

26:59.137 --> 27:03.655
- We have any little recourse
on the Reservation land?

27:03.758 --> 27:06.137
- Civil maybe, but if
you're talking prosecution,

27:06.241 --> 27:08.413
we need friends in
the U.S. Attorney's Office.

27:11.206 --> 27:12.655
- Make some.

27:12.758 --> 27:14.413
[applause]

27:14.517 --> 27:15.206
Hello, Trent.

27:15.310 --> 27:17.034
- John.

27:17.137 --> 27:20.931
I wouldn't wish the week you're
having on my mother-in-law.

27:21.034 --> 27:23.827
[laughing]
- Well, it's only Tuesday.

27:24.448 --> 27:25.379
- 50, 60, 60.

27:25.482 --> 27:27.344
Now 70. 70 now.

27:27.448 --> 27:29.206
75, now bid at 80, 80.

27:29.310 --> 27:29.827
- John.

27:32.482 --> 27:33.724
- This is not the day, Dirk.

27:33.827 --> 27:35.344
- The word has it
you're hiring.

27:35.448 --> 27:38.275
- Cowboys, not criminals.

27:39.379 --> 27:40.206
- I can't stop him.

27:40.310 --> 27:42.655
You can.

27:43.586 --> 27:46.482
Jimmy's the only family
I have left.

27:46.586 --> 27:49.103
The favor's to me,
not to him.

27:50.241 --> 27:51.655
Please.

27:54.172 --> 27:55.241
Please.

27:59.586 --> 28:01.068
- We're gonna do this my way,
all right?

28:01.172 --> 28:03.275
You understand? My way.
- Yeah.

28:03.379 --> 28:04.793
I remember when your way
was the only way,

28:04.896 --> 28:07.758
and the world
was better for that.

28:09.551 --> 28:10.448
- Hello, Governor.
- John.

28:10.551 --> 28:11.827
How are you?

28:12.655 --> 28:14.000
Thank you.

28:14.931 --> 28:17.379
Jamie did well
at the hearing.

28:17.482 --> 28:19.758
- It's easy to do well
when the outcome's decided.

28:19.862 --> 28:20.689
- I couldn't hit it
if he didn't tee it up,

28:20.793 --> 28:23.551
and my offer
still stands, John.

28:23.655 --> 28:25.068
- Yeah, well...

28:25.172 --> 28:27.758
I don't want him in politics.

28:27.862 --> 28:29.586
- He's already in politics.

28:29.689 --> 28:32.310
- Yeah, with
a constituency of one.

28:32.413 --> 28:34.172
- [laughs]

28:35.655 --> 28:38.862
How concerned should I be
about this issue on the Res?

28:40.034 --> 28:42.689
- It's a new chief
showing off for his voters.

28:42.793 --> 28:43.896
We've all done it.

28:47.379 --> 28:49.689
[applause]
- Well...

28:49.793 --> 28:51.965
we should schedule
a lunch.

28:54.724 --> 28:56.517
- I could use a lunch.

28:56.620 --> 29:00.482
[background chatter]

29:03.448 --> 29:06.275
[solemn music]

29:06.379 --> 29:13.137
♪

29:14.896 --> 29:15.862
- Sold it to you. 135.
Sold it, 135.

29:15.965 --> 29:18.000
[indistinct chatter]
[cattle lowing]

29:34.482 --> 29:35.758
- You were right.

29:35.862 --> 29:37.034
They're building a city.

29:38.689 --> 29:40.000
Goodnight, Daddy.

29:40.103 --> 29:44.482
- Goodnight, sweetheart.
Good to have you home.

29:44.586 --> 29:46.413
[pensive string music]

29:46.517 --> 29:54.379
♪

30:19.965 --> 30:21.379
- [clicking lips]

30:21.482 --> 30:25.206
[clicking tongue]

30:25.310 --> 30:27.413
That's it.

30:27.517 --> 30:30.379
Come on. That's it.

30:35.172 --> 30:37.793
That's it.
That's it, buddy.

30:37.896 --> 30:39.896
- Got tiger stripes
on his legs.

30:41.827 --> 30:44.482
You know what that means,
don't you?

30:44.586 --> 30:46.793
- [exhales sharply]

30:46.896 --> 30:49.275
Spanish blood.
- Pure.

30:50.344 --> 30:52.586
One of his ancestors
probably bucked a conquistador

30:52.689 --> 30:55.413
and took to the hills.

30:55.517 --> 30:56.655
You manage to break his spirit,

30:56.758 --> 30:57.965
no horse will
serve you better.

30:58.068 --> 31:01.655
- He'll serve me just fine
with spirit intact.

31:01.758 --> 31:03.344
- Yeah.

31:03.448 --> 31:05.000
I used to think
the same thing at your age.

31:07.068 --> 31:08.000
Hope you prove me wrong.

31:10.896 --> 31:12.827
- I didn't know them
were your cattle.

31:12.931 --> 31:14.068
- Would it have made
a difference?

31:19.172 --> 31:21.689
You don't want to be
on the wrong side of this, son.

31:21.793 --> 31:24.068
- Yeah, well, the list of
things I don't want is endless.

31:24.172 --> 31:25.758
You telling me what to do
is one of them.

31:25.862 --> 31:27.206
- I'm not telling you
what to do.

31:27.310 --> 31:29.172
I just don't want you
to get in trouble.

31:29.275 --> 31:31.586
- Well, if I'd have known
there was sides,

31:31.689 --> 31:33.448
I wouldn't have been
there at all.

31:37.344 --> 31:41.275
- Good lord, even here
the world just keeps on coming.

31:42.517 --> 31:44.620
- Rough week, huh?

31:44.724 --> 31:46.689
- Yeah.

31:46.793 --> 31:49.241
One only a grandson
could fix.

31:49.344 --> 31:50.931
Thought I'd come see

31:51.034 --> 31:53.000
Tate play in the dirt,
maybe even join him.

31:56.689 --> 32:00.137
- He's at Monica's parents.

32:00.241 --> 32:04.000
- I guess the early grandpa
gets the worm, huh?

32:12.000 --> 32:14.137
Can I give you
some advice, Kayce?

32:15.793 --> 32:17.896
Someday your son's
gonna test you.

32:19.310 --> 32:20.689
He's gonna force you
to make a decision

32:20.793 --> 32:22.724
that not only determines
his future

32:22.827 --> 32:25.206
but your place in it.

32:25.310 --> 32:27.413
I want you to remember me
standing here, son,

32:27.517 --> 32:29.931
before you make that decision,
because this--

32:30.034 --> 32:33.482
this is a consequence
of choosing wrong.

32:37.724 --> 32:38.793
- Anything else?

32:38.896 --> 32:42.000
- I just want to
know him, Kayce.

32:43.482 --> 32:46.379
- You know him.
- No, I don't. I don't.

32:46.482 --> 32:47.586
We've met,
but I don't really know him.

32:47.689 --> 32:50.103
And he doesn't know me.

32:52.379 --> 32:56.862
Is it too much to ask that you
help make that happen?

32:56.965 --> 32:59.517
- [humorless chuckle]

32:59.620 --> 33:02.689
You've always asked too much.

33:14.758 --> 33:17.689
[clicking tongue]

33:17.793 --> 33:19.689
[truck starts]

33:28.793 --> 33:30.586
- What was he doing here?

33:31.551 --> 33:32.413
- [sighs] Who knows?

33:32.517 --> 33:33.620
- Dad!

33:33.724 --> 33:36.620
Is this for me?

33:48.206 --> 33:51.241
[hard rock music playing]

33:51.344 --> 33:58.172
♪

34:08.827 --> 34:11.103
[music stops]

34:13.931 --> 34:15.275
- You Jimmy?

34:16.827 --> 34:18.482
Dirk Hurdstram's boy?

34:20.379 --> 34:21.585
- [stammers]

34:21.688 --> 34:24.034
- You alone, Jimmy?

34:24.137 --> 34:25.862
I'll take that as a yes.

34:25.965 --> 34:27.551
[Taser zapping]

34:36.034 --> 34:38.516
You're a two-time loser,
Jimmy.

34:38.620 --> 34:41.172
One more felony,
and they throw away the keys.

34:42.413 --> 34:45.413
You know what? You might
do all right in prison.

34:46.172 --> 34:48.241
You got the lips for it.

34:48.344 --> 34:50.344
- You're either a servant
or a king in this place,

34:50.447 --> 34:52.688
and I ain't no fucking servant.

34:52.793 --> 34:54.757
- No, no.

34:58.758 --> 35:01.103
You're a thief.

35:01.206 --> 35:02.655
- Oh, what the fuck, man?

35:02.758 --> 35:04.620
What the fuck, man?

35:04.724 --> 35:05.517
Wait, wait, wait!

35:05.620 --> 35:08.517
Wait, wait, wait!
Wait, wait!

35:08.620 --> 35:10.172
Fucking psycho, wait!

35:10.275 --> 35:12.482
- Jimmy, I'm gonna give
you two choices.

35:12.586 --> 35:14.206
One is I take you
and all this shit,

35:14.310 --> 35:17.068
and I drive you down
to the sheriff's office,

35:17.172 --> 35:19.620
and it's good riddance
to your sorry ass,

35:19.724 --> 35:22.275
or you prove that you
deserve another chance.

35:22.379 --> 35:26.241
From what I can see, you don't,
but it ain't up to me.

35:26.344 --> 35:28.000
- You're with the Yellowstone?

35:28.103 --> 35:30.758
- It's getting cold, Jimmy.

35:30.862 --> 35:33.137
You know what? Fuck it. I'm
taking you to the sheriff's.

35:33.241 --> 35:35.137
- Wait, just--
- Just get up.

35:37.758 --> 35:39.827
- Why would John Dutton
give a shit about me?

35:39.931 --> 35:42.137
- He doesn't.

35:44.034 --> 35:45.344
But he will.

35:48.172 --> 35:51.620
Now, you be a man about it.
Don't scream.

35:51.724 --> 35:54.137
- [breathing hard]

35:54.241 --> 35:57.275
[branding iron sizzles]
- [groaning]

36:04.793 --> 36:05.344
[groans]

36:09.172 --> 36:11.793
- You know where the ranch is?

36:14.103 --> 36:15.793
You start Monday.

36:22.137 --> 36:25.137
- Hey, we need
a new dishwasher.

36:26.586 --> 36:29.482
- I notice you never ask for
appliances with your pants on.

36:29.586 --> 36:31.827
- Number one, I make more money

36:31.931 --> 36:33.620
than you do, cowboy.
- Oh, yeah?

36:33.724 --> 36:35.482
- And number two,
I already bought it.

36:35.586 --> 36:36.620
No pants is so you don't bitch

36:36.724 --> 36:40.172
about driving to Billings
to pick it up.

36:40.275 --> 36:42.896
- Ugh, Billings.

36:44.103 --> 36:45.586
- It's so far.

36:49.241 --> 36:50.310
Tell me about today.

36:58.137 --> 37:00.413
- He just wants to know
his grandson.

37:02.344 --> 37:04.517
I guess we could give him that.
What do you think?

37:05.344 --> 37:07.689
- You know what I think.

37:07.793 --> 37:11.551
But we'll give it
to him anyway.

37:11.655 --> 37:13.655
It'll happen to us too
someday.

37:14.965 --> 37:19.103
Tate'll move away
and have a family of his own,

37:19.206 --> 37:21.862
and all we'll get
is little fixes.

37:23.586 --> 37:27.896
- That is the meanest thing
you've ever said to me.

37:28.000 --> 37:29.379
- I know, baby, but it's true.

37:35.862 --> 37:37.551
We can make another.

37:38.758 --> 37:41.206
That way when he leaves,
it won't hurt so bad.

37:53.551 --> 37:56.655
[soft music]

37:56.758 --> 38:03.896
♪

38:13.655 --> 38:14.655
- Hold on.

38:18.620 --> 38:19.482
1138.

38:23.137 --> 38:24.793
- 1138.

38:25.931 --> 38:27.379
Lost one last year.

38:27.482 --> 38:28.379
Old gal just turned 11.

38:30.275 --> 38:32.206
- Get rid of her.

38:34.034 --> 38:36.103
- [clears throat]

38:36.206 --> 38:38.103
- I needed you at the auction.

38:38.206 --> 38:40.862
- I was at the auction.

38:40.965 --> 38:42.517
- I don't mean checking brands.

38:42.620 --> 38:45.206
- Dad, I stand in bullshit
12 hours a day.

38:45.310 --> 38:46.724
I'm not gonna do it at night.
That's Jamie's job.

38:46.827 --> 38:48.206
- You can't run this place

38:48.310 --> 38:49.655
if you won't interact
with the people, Lee.

38:49.758 --> 38:50.827
- I'm running it right now.
- This ain't running it.

38:50.931 --> 38:53.068
- Don't start with me.
- This ain't running it!

38:53.172 --> 38:55.344
This is working it.

38:58.482 --> 38:59.965
God damn it, 38 years old,

39:00.068 --> 39:01.965
you still don't know
the difference.

39:07.103 --> 39:09.275
- Shit, one's down.

39:13.206 --> 39:15.413
[cows lowing]

39:45.000 --> 39:46.517
- Looks like a breech.

39:46.620 --> 39:49.448
- Can we get her up?
- No, we'll pull it--

39:49.551 --> 39:53.000
We'll pull it while she's down.

39:53.103 --> 39:54.586
- You got her?

39:55.931 --> 39:56.758
Okay, ready?

39:56.862 --> 39:57.896
[lowing]

39:58.000 --> 40:00.689
I'm sorry.

40:00.793 --> 40:02.241
[cow huffing]

40:02.344 --> 40:05.689
- You feel the legs?
- Not yet.

40:05.793 --> 40:07.172
[cow grunts]

40:07.275 --> 40:09.586
- Easy, mama. Easy, easy.

40:09.689 --> 40:11.758
- Okay, got them, I got them.
All right, tell me when.

40:13.482 --> 40:16.103
[straining] Tell me when.
[cow moaning]

40:16.206 --> 40:17.862
- All right, go.
- [grunts]

40:17.965 --> 40:21.448
- Shh, easy, mama.

40:21.551 --> 40:22.551
Shh.

40:22.655 --> 40:24.482
- [grunting]

40:24.586 --> 40:27.689
[lowing]

40:27.793 --> 40:32.241
[both cows lowing]

40:47.862 --> 40:50.379
- [sighs, laughs]

40:50.482 --> 40:52.551
- [sighs, groans]

40:55.724 --> 40:56.551
- Whew.

41:03.517 --> 41:05.827
- When you look at that calf,
what do you see?

41:09.551 --> 41:11.517
- I see a life
I got to feed and defend

41:11.620 --> 41:13.931
until it grows up and feeds me.

41:16.379 --> 41:19.000
- That's what
a cowboy should see.

41:22.448 --> 41:24.241
But a cattleman sees
a $293 investment

41:24.344 --> 41:29.000
worth $1,100 in seven months

41:29.103 --> 41:31.000
whether it feeds anyone or not.

41:33.137 --> 41:36.448
- Wish I saw it
different, Dad.

41:38.689 --> 41:42.310
- Well, we see it
the way we see it, son.

41:44.931 --> 41:47.965
[cattle lowing]

42:10.586 --> 42:13.413
- Well, if it isn't
bachelor number two

42:13.517 --> 42:16.965
up at the crack of 9:30
and dressed to seize the day.

42:17.068 --> 42:18.655
- Yeah.

42:18.758 --> 42:20.724
It's Saturday.
- No weekends on a ranch.

42:20.827 --> 42:22.482
You know that.

42:22.586 --> 42:25.103
- Nice to see
you're still smoking.

42:25.206 --> 42:25.793
- [laughs]

42:27.034 --> 42:30.620
Well, women in this family
don't live much past 40 anyway,

42:30.724 --> 42:34.103
so I might as well
enjoy my time.

42:34.206 --> 42:36.482
- What are you doing here?

42:38.448 --> 42:40.517
- Same thing I always do.

42:41.689 --> 42:42.724
Fixing something you couldn't.

42:44.758 --> 42:45.551
You missed breakfast.
[door opens and closes]

42:53.379 --> 42:54.965
[buffalo grunting]

42:59.068 --> 43:02.172
- Now, what the hell are we
supposed to do with buffalo?

43:02.275 --> 43:02.655
- You'll see.

43:03.862 --> 43:06.655
- Yeah, well how much
these sumbitches cost?

43:06.758 --> 43:08.724
- Well, they ain't cheap.

43:29.655 --> 43:32.137
[horse whinnies]

43:39.000 --> 43:41.172
I was thinking
about you yesterday.

43:41.275 --> 43:42.758
A friend of mine
in Jackson Hole

43:42.862 --> 43:44.793
was talking about their rodeo.

43:44.896 --> 43:47.517
Bozeman doesn't have one.
Why not?

43:47.620 --> 43:49.517
- It's 'cause nobody here
cares about rodeos.

43:49.620 --> 43:50.724
- Oh, you're wrong, John.

43:50.827 --> 43:54.724
Every millionaire I know
wants to be a cowboy.

43:54.827 --> 43:57.517
Authenticity's the one thing
that money can't buy.

43:57.620 --> 43:58.965
It'd be good for Bozeman

43:59.068 --> 44:01.862
and a great way
to honor men like you.

44:01.965 --> 44:03.689
- Yeah, well, parading us
in front of your friends,

44:03.793 --> 44:07.689
Dan, isn't an honor.
It's a--it's an insult.

44:07.793 --> 44:09.689
You want to build subdivisions,

44:09.793 --> 44:10.758
move to Dallas.
I won't have them here.

44:13.827 --> 44:16.137
Yeah, that's right.
Nothing happens in this valley

44:16.241 --> 44:18.655
I don't know about.

44:18.758 --> 44:20.793
- It's called progress, John,

44:20.896 --> 44:23.344
and progress doesn't need
your permission.

44:23.448 --> 44:26.241
- Yeah, in this valley it does.

44:26.344 --> 44:27.896
- What do you care
what I build?

44:28.000 --> 44:29.655
You expect me to believe
that you're concerned

44:29.758 --> 44:31.758
about the environment?

44:31.862 --> 44:34.724
You raise cattle,
you fucking hypocrite.

44:34.827 --> 44:37.310
You know what I think it is?
I think it's ego.

44:37.413 --> 44:39.103
I think it chaps your ass

44:39.206 --> 44:41.241
to walk through a grocery store
and nobody knows who you are.

44:41.344 --> 44:42.206
- You bet your ass it does

44:42.310 --> 44:44.620
because every family
you move in

44:44.724 --> 44:46.448
moves a family I know out.

44:46.551 --> 44:47.862
- With every winner,
there's a loser.

44:47.965 --> 44:50.413
- First thing you said
I agree with.

44:50.517 --> 44:52.344
- Can't stop it, John.

44:52.448 --> 44:54.413
- Watch me.

44:54.517 --> 44:56.655
- Go ahead, say it.

44:56.758 --> 44:58.758
It'll make a lawsuit
much simpler.

44:58.862 --> 45:00.310
Say, "Stop building or else."

45:00.413 --> 45:02.000
[horse grunting]

45:02.103 --> 45:03.620
- I'm skipping straight
to "or else"

45:03.724 --> 45:05.896
with you, you cocksucker,

45:06.000 --> 45:09.689
and from now on "or else"
is all you get.

45:12.827 --> 45:14.586
And by the way...

45:16.965 --> 45:19.275
you owe me a horse,
you son of a bitch.

45:19.379 --> 45:22.241
[foreboding music]

45:22.344 --> 45:29.758
♪

45:33.275 --> 45:34.896
- He's not there.

45:42.482 --> 45:44.068
You look nervous, Rip.

45:45.344 --> 45:46.689
Like a stray dog who can't
enjoy being in the house

45:46.793 --> 45:49.862
'cause he's so worried
about the broom.

45:51.827 --> 45:52.758
- You're up early.

45:55.689 --> 45:58.103
- I don't really sleep.

45:58.206 --> 45:59.206
- Yeah, well, they say
spiders don't, so...

45:59.310 --> 46:01.758
- [chuckling] Oh.

46:09.517 --> 46:11.862
- What are you doing?

46:11.965 --> 46:14.068
- Adjusting my web.

46:15.310 --> 46:16.413
- [ahem]

46:16.517 --> 46:18.862
- You know, life's not
that complicated, Rip.

46:18.965 --> 46:21.931
You either walk
on down the hall...

46:24.206 --> 46:26.793
Or fuck me.

46:26.896 --> 46:29.724
[dresser thudding]

46:29.827 --> 46:31.965
[both breathing heavily]

46:35.482 --> 46:38.758
[moaning]

46:59.620 --> 47:01.586
- There's a music festival

47:01.689 --> 47:04.379
in Livingston this weekend.

47:04.482 --> 47:06.068
You want to go with me?

47:11.413 --> 47:13.758
- You ruin it every time.

47:17.586 --> 47:19.034
That's funny.

47:20.344 --> 47:23.206
I always remember your dick
as being bigger.

47:26.275 --> 47:29.137
I guess that's just
the nostalgic in me.

47:37.344 --> 47:40.655
[soft guitar music]

47:40.758 --> 47:47.896
♪

47:48.000 --> 47:50.689
- Is this where you ate
ice cream when you were a boy?

47:51.862 --> 47:53.827
- This wasn't here
when I was a boy.

47:54.655 --> 47:56.034
None of this was.

47:57.655 --> 48:00.206
I will say this though.

48:00.310 --> 48:02.000
These transplants sure
can make some ice cream.

48:03.586 --> 48:06.379
- What's a transplant?

48:07.482 --> 48:08.827
- It's, um,

48:08.931 --> 48:12.103
a person who moves
to a place,

48:12.206 --> 48:13.586
and then they try
to make that place

48:13.689 --> 48:14.551
just like the place
they left.

48:14.655 --> 48:17.206
- That don't make sense.

48:18.965 --> 48:20.448
- Not one bit.

48:25.965 --> 48:28.965
- It's all right.
Here. Give me that.

48:29.068 --> 48:30.862
Hold that in both hands
and eat it from the top

48:30.965 --> 48:32.379
so it don't fall off
again.

48:57.862 --> 49:00.000
- Is he a transplant?

49:00.862 --> 49:03.965
- They're all transplants.

49:07.689 --> 49:10.551
[country rock music]

49:10.655 --> 49:17.931
♪

49:26.620 --> 49:29.448
- What's the matter, Dad?

49:31.689 --> 49:33.379
- Nothing, buddy.

49:35.103 --> 49:37.758
Just hope I don't regret this.

49:37.862 --> 49:42.137
[Whiskey Myers'
"On the River"]

49:42.241 --> 49:44.517
- ♪ Lord Jebediah,
won't you let me down ♪

49:44.620 --> 49:48.137
♪ Promise me a place
from here much better ♪

49:48.241 --> 49:51.413
♪

49:51.517 --> 49:53.275
♪ There's the aftermath
them ties and tracks ♪

49:53.379 --> 49:56.517
♪ Your red dog, won't you
give it all up for me? ♪

49:56.620 --> 50:01.758
♪

50:01.862 --> 50:03.655
♪ I'm set to save a dime
a day ♪

50:03.758 --> 50:06.517
♪ And get a log cabin
down there by the river ♪

50:06.620 --> 50:10.689
♪

50:10.793 --> 50:12.275
[car door shuts]

50:16.137 --> 50:18.137
- Thought I'd bring
the fix to you.

50:26.896 --> 50:27.758
- You know how to ride a horse?

50:27.862 --> 50:30.000
- Course I do.
I'm Indian.

50:33.655 --> 50:35.103
- [straining] Yeah, maybe so.

50:36.827 --> 50:38.275
But you're a cowboy today.

50:41.551 --> 50:42.103
Thank you for this.

50:44.655 --> 50:46.068
- Well, shit, Kayce,

50:46.172 --> 50:48.758
I've dated women
with shorter hair than you.

50:48.862 --> 50:49.793
- Yeah, you sure
they were women, Lee?

50:49.896 --> 50:50.103
- I know.

50:51.655 --> 50:53.103
[both grunt]

50:58.310 --> 50:59.482
- Hey, cowboy.

51:04.206 --> 51:08.103
Last time I saw you,
that was high and tight.

51:09.724 --> 51:11.172
- How's Mr. Daniel?

51:14.448 --> 51:16.034
Good for you.

51:16.137 --> 51:17.931
- Yeah, you're the only one
who shares that opinion.

51:18.034 --> 51:20.275
- That's 'cause I'm the only
one who got to know him.

51:20.379 --> 51:21.517
- [laughs]

51:21.620 --> 51:22.034
What are you doing here?

51:24.172 --> 51:26.586
- Closure, I guess. You?

51:26.689 --> 51:28.275
- Penance.

51:28.379 --> 51:29.413
- Not sure you'll
find that here.

51:29.517 --> 51:33.344
- Penance you earn.
Closure you find.

51:33.448 --> 51:35.517
Look somewhere else,
and you might.

51:37.275 --> 51:40.931
- Hey, Kayce, let's go.
Grab a horse.

51:41.034 --> 51:44.206
- [sighs]
Any chance you'd join us?

51:45.344 --> 51:46.103
- I don't get near
those fucking things.

51:52.827 --> 51:54.827
- Yah!
Move it!

51:54.931 --> 51:56.724
[men shouting, whistling]

51:56.827 --> 51:58.655
[buffalo snorting]
[horses neighing]

52:00.413 --> 52:03.586
[buffalo snorting]
[men shouting]

52:03.689 --> 52:06.965
[somber music]

52:07.068 --> 52:09.896
♪

52:10.000 --> 52:10.758
- Let me do it, Grandpa.

52:10.862 --> 52:12.965
- Can you do it?
- Yeah.

52:13.068 --> 52:14.965
Hi-yah!

52:16.137 --> 52:17.241
This horse ain't got any go.

52:17.862 --> 52:21.068
- He's got some go. Hold on.

52:21.172 --> 52:22.689
I'll get him going for you.

52:22.793 --> 52:24.103
- Race you.
- Yah!

52:24.206 --> 52:25.448
Yah!

52:28.655 --> 52:29.620
[clicks tongue]

52:29.724 --> 52:33.172
- Yah!
- Whoo!

52:41.241 --> 52:42.241
- Think they should hold here.

52:44.206 --> 52:46.482
[men shouting distantly]

52:46.586 --> 52:49.103
Kayce might be the only man
who can outride him.

52:52.517 --> 52:54.034
- Just might be.

53:01.689 --> 53:03.655
[quiet music]

53:03.758 --> 53:12.137
♪

53:12.241 --> 53:14.655
- Fish on. Tate.

53:20.862 --> 53:22.344
- All right, buddy.

53:25.206 --> 53:27.758
- Here, grab--grab that rod.

53:27.862 --> 53:29.275
- Reel him in.

53:31.275 --> 53:32.344
There you go.
Reel it in, buddy.

53:35.551 --> 53:35.965
- [chuckles]

53:36.068 --> 53:37.931
- Whoo!

53:38.034 --> 53:41.482
- Lee, get my horse.
Whoo!

53:41.586 --> 53:43.310
Little late in the year
for that.

53:46.862 --> 53:47.172
- Got him.

53:49.275 --> 53:50.793
- I caught a fish!

53:50.896 --> 53:51.758
- Can you pull him up?

53:51.862 --> 53:54.413
- Look at that.

53:54.517 --> 53:55.620
- Whoo!

53:55.724 --> 53:57.862
- That's a big one, huh?

53:57.965 --> 53:59.655
- Yeah.
- Oh, she's pretty.

53:59.758 --> 54:01.241
- Yeah.
- Look at that one.

54:05.793 --> 54:07.551
- Any luck?

54:25.206 --> 54:26.724
- Here, wait, don't touch it.

54:26.827 --> 54:27.275
It's kind of hot.

54:29.551 --> 54:30.620
Careful.

54:30.724 --> 54:32.827
- You're gonna raise him
on a reservation?

54:32.931 --> 54:35.931
- People do it every day.

54:36.034 --> 54:38.413
- 'Cause they have
no choice, Kayce.

54:38.517 --> 54:40.724
- Yeah, looks like
you're ready to eat.

54:42.206 --> 54:44.103
- It's a good day.

54:45.068 --> 54:46.862
- Every day, just like this.

54:46.965 --> 54:49.448
- Who are you kidding?

54:49.551 --> 54:51.551
Bet you haven't
fished here in years.

54:51.655 --> 54:55.275
- Only thing we haven't done
in years is see you, Kayce.

54:55.379 --> 54:57.724
- Well, he told me to leave.

54:57.827 --> 54:59.172
- He told us all
to leave.

54:59.275 --> 55:01.379
You were just the only one
who did.

55:03.241 --> 55:06.586
- It's different.
You know that.

55:06.689 --> 55:09.689
- Right, so you're gonna
raise him in that meth-filled

55:09.793 --> 55:10.793
desert to prove a point.

55:10.896 --> 55:14.000
- What I'm proving
you'll never understand.

55:14.103 --> 55:15.724
[both chuckle]

55:15.827 --> 55:17.000
- [chuckles]

55:17.103 --> 55:19.482
Shit, I miss being young.

55:19.586 --> 55:21.206
You wake up in the morning,

55:21.310 --> 55:23.379
and you just keep right
on dreaming, huh?

55:24.758 --> 55:27.793
- You're a 38-year-old bachelor
living in your father's house,

55:27.896 --> 55:30.689
working 100-hour weeks
for a nibble of his approval.

55:30.793 --> 55:33.103
Is that the dream, Lee?

55:33.206 --> 55:35.827
Sure as shit ain't mine.

55:42.206 --> 55:43.793
Hey.
- [laughs]

55:43.896 --> 55:44.655
- Hey!

55:44.758 --> 55:47.137
Don't throw things at my dad.

55:47.241 --> 55:48.172
- Hey, hey, hey, hey.
- Whoa!

55:48.275 --> 55:49.172
Oh.
- Fucker.

55:49.275 --> 55:50.896
- Tate!
- Whoa!

55:51.000 --> 55:53.482
- [laughs]

55:54.448 --> 55:55.379
- [laughing] It's okay, buddy.

55:58.241 --> 55:59.689
We're just brothers
arguing, man.

55:59.793 --> 56:01.103
Nobody's mad, okay?

56:01.206 --> 56:02.827
It's all right.

56:04.034 --> 56:06.482
- You gonna tell me there's
no fight in that blood?

56:08.172 --> 56:10.137
- He's right though.

56:10.241 --> 56:11.655
It is a good day.

56:13.206 --> 56:15.793
- He said "fucker."

56:15.896 --> 56:18.310
[laughter]

56:24.068 --> 56:25.896
- You got green for water.

56:26.000 --> 56:27.586
Blue is sewage, yellow for gas.

56:27.689 --> 56:29.586
Driveways are marked in pink

56:29.689 --> 56:31.172
and corner buildings in red.

56:31.275 --> 56:34.551
If I were to dam the river...

56:35.862 --> 56:38.517
I'd do it right there
around the bend.

56:38.620 --> 56:40.655
- That's where
they're doing it.

56:42.310 --> 56:45.241
- That's your property
upstream?

56:46.137 --> 56:48.655
Now, I'm not gonna lie to you.

56:48.758 --> 56:51.413
There's gonna be a severe
impact to your land.

56:51.517 --> 56:53.517
Erosion's my biggest concern.

56:56.310 --> 56:58.379
- My biggest concern
is a subdivision

56:58.482 --> 56:59.275
sucking on our river.

56:59.379 --> 57:01.275
- There's nothing you can do.

57:01.379 --> 57:04.793
On their land,
it's their river.

57:04.896 --> 57:06.448
I mean, I can't stop
the river from flowing.

57:16.586 --> 57:18.793
- I don't want you
to stop it, Ron.

57:18.896 --> 57:20.517
I want you to move it.

57:32.206 --> 57:33.655
- How's it going over there?

57:33.758 --> 57:34.517
- Oh, hey,
we got to make the dressing.

57:34.620 --> 57:36.310
- Oh, okay,
I'll make it.

57:36.413 --> 57:39.448
[TV playing]

57:40.655 --> 57:42.068
- How could you give him
a D, Monica?

57:42.172 --> 57:43.482
He's your nephew.

57:43.586 --> 57:46.000
- The D was a gift, believe me.

57:46.103 --> 57:47.448
- What can I say?

57:47.551 --> 57:50.379
Math is not his thing,
like his father.

57:50.482 --> 57:51.724
- Well, he better
make it his thing,

57:51.827 --> 57:53.448
or he's gonna end up
like his father.

57:55.482 --> 57:57.620
He's my brother.
I can say it.

57:57.724 --> 58:00.551
- When I get my steers,
I'm gonna take one,

58:00.655 --> 58:03.137
carve out a porterhouse
the size of a radiator.

58:03.241 --> 58:05.310
[both laugh]

58:05.413 --> 58:06.965
- They divvying up the cattle?

58:09.206 --> 58:10.655
- You don't like it,

58:10.758 --> 58:13.586
maybe you shouldn't
have rounded them up.

58:15.551 --> 58:17.586
- They ain't yours to divvy.

58:22.000 --> 58:24.034
- What is that one?

58:25.275 --> 58:28.896
- It's a Silver Star.

58:29.000 --> 58:29.655
- You got one of those?

58:32.827 --> 58:35.620
What do you have
to do to win one?

58:35.724 --> 58:38.862
- You got to kill someone
to get one of those.

58:38.965 --> 58:40.482
Ain't that right, Kayce?

58:42.241 --> 58:44.517
- What about that one?

58:46.103 --> 58:47.655
- That's the Navy Cross.

58:49.862 --> 58:52.793
You wouldn't believe what
I had to do to get that one.

58:52.896 --> 58:55.482
[car approaching]

58:59.551 --> 59:01.413
- What's he doing here?

59:06.379 --> 59:07.896
- Well, I hope
I'm not intruding.

59:08.000 --> 59:09.965
- Of course not,
but my grandfather's not here.

59:10.068 --> 59:12.413
- Well, I'm not here to see
your grandfather.

59:14.827 --> 59:16.793
I want to thank you
for helping the other day.

59:17.310 --> 59:20.103
I don't know your father.

59:20.206 --> 59:22.586
I hope it didn't put you
in an uncomfortable position.

59:24.793 --> 59:25.689
- Well, if you plan
on keeping his cattle,

59:25.793 --> 59:28.724
you'll get to
know him real well.

59:28.827 --> 59:30.448
- [laughs]

59:30.551 --> 59:34.275
- Those are bargaining chips,
a means to an end.

59:34.379 --> 59:37.655
Politicians are like crabs.
We move sideways to go forward.

59:37.758 --> 59:39.586
- Well, that won't get you
too far with him.

59:41.896 --> 59:43.655
- An honest man?

59:43.758 --> 59:45.586
- He says he'll do something,
you're not gonna stop him,

59:45.689 --> 59:48.172
if you call that honest.

59:48.275 --> 59:50.275
- I do.

59:50.379 --> 59:52.724
It's a rare thing
these days.

59:52.827 --> 59:55.413
- What do you want from me?

59:55.517 --> 59:57.689
- To help me

59:57.793 --> 01:00:01.931
understand the man
I'm negotiating with.

01:00:04.068 --> 01:00:06.758
- Well, he's reasonable
till he's provoked.

01:00:08.862 --> 01:00:11.413
Then reason
don't factor in at all.

01:00:13.551 --> 01:00:16.137
Doubt that helps you,
but that's who he is.

01:00:16.241 --> 01:00:18.896
- It helps.

01:00:20.724 --> 01:00:22.862
Thank you for your time.

01:00:22.965 --> 01:00:24.586
Have a good evening.

01:00:33.344 --> 01:00:34.275
- [exhales deeply]

01:00:34.379 --> 01:00:35.517
[clicks lips]

01:00:37.655 --> 01:00:40.034
- You're not
joining him?

01:00:40.137 --> 01:00:42.517
- You didn't ask me here
to hunt.

01:00:42.620 --> 01:00:45.103
I'm here to talk cattle.

01:00:45.206 --> 01:00:46.344
- They don't belong to you.

01:00:46.448 --> 01:00:49.482
- They don't belong
to you either.

01:00:49.586 --> 01:00:50.551
They belong to the people now.

01:00:50.655 --> 01:00:52.586
- Every one of them
wears a brand.

01:00:52.689 --> 01:00:55.137
If anybody tries
to move them off the Res--

01:00:55.241 --> 01:00:57.344
- They'll never leave the Res.

01:00:57.448 --> 01:01:00.448
We'll use them to raise calves,
wear our brand.

01:01:00.551 --> 01:01:02.586
- I understand
your position, Thomas,

01:01:02.689 --> 01:01:05.551
and what you think
you need to do...

01:01:05.655 --> 01:01:06.655
but I won't allow you
to make

01:01:06.758 --> 01:01:08.965
victims of the people
who elected me

01:01:09.068 --> 01:01:11.620
just to appease the people
who elected you.

01:01:11.724 --> 01:01:14.758
- Your people don't know
the concept of victim.

01:01:18.413 --> 01:01:21.103
- Let's keep this about
cattle.

01:01:21.206 --> 01:01:22.344
If you act like
a thief, Thomas,

01:01:22.448 --> 01:01:24.448
I will treat you like one.

01:01:24.551 --> 01:01:26.206
- How can you stand there
on a ranch

01:01:26.310 --> 01:01:28.586
the size of Rhode Island

01:01:28.689 --> 01:01:31.172
and accuse me of theft?

01:01:31.275 --> 01:01:33.724
Is this your idea of respect?

01:01:33.827 --> 01:01:36.655
Letting some crippled old man
ride his lame horse

01:01:36.758 --> 01:01:38.724
out toward
your half-tame buffalo

01:01:38.827 --> 01:01:40.413
so he can pretend
to be something

01:01:40.517 --> 01:01:43.379
we haven't been in a century?

01:01:43.482 --> 01:01:46.275
[somber music]

01:01:46.379 --> 01:01:49.862
♪

01:01:49.965 --> 01:01:52.448
- Whoo!

01:01:53.379 --> 01:01:55.275
- Look what you've
reduced us to.

01:01:55.379 --> 01:01:57.000
[clicks tongue]

01:02:03.413 --> 01:02:05.931
- Here's another one.

01:02:06.034 --> 01:02:08.620
[chicken clucking]

01:02:08.724 --> 01:02:11.241
You lay everywhere
but the coop.

01:02:15.103 --> 01:02:17.137
[children chattering]

01:02:20.517 --> 01:02:22.620
- [speaking native language]

01:02:22.724 --> 01:02:25.068
- [speaking
native language]

01:02:32.448 --> 01:02:33.620
Backstraps.

01:02:33.724 --> 01:02:35.517
- Staying for dinner?
- Can't.

01:02:35.620 --> 01:02:37.275
Just need a few words
with this young buck here.

01:02:37.379 --> 01:02:39.896
Can you give us a minute?

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:43.344
- If you can say it to him,
you can say it to me.

01:02:43.448 --> 01:02:47.482
- Hard to talk about you when
you're standing here, darling.

01:02:47.586 --> 01:02:49.724
- Come on, Tate.
We're being sent to our room.

01:02:51.655 --> 01:02:54.000
- The Nation will
keep the cattle.

01:02:54.724 --> 01:02:58.379
Your father will try
to take them back.

01:02:58.482 --> 01:03:00.827
He has every right.

01:03:00.931 --> 01:03:06.137
We had every right to take
them, so now we will fight.

01:03:07.551 --> 01:03:10.103
- It's his fight, not mine.

01:03:10.206 --> 01:03:14.758
- You will be judged
for the actions of your father.

01:03:14.862 --> 01:03:18.310
If you do nothing, you will
be judged for that too.

01:03:18.413 --> 01:03:20.724
They all will.

01:03:20.827 --> 01:03:24.724
Maybe it's best you go home
for a while, eh?

01:03:24.827 --> 01:03:26.344
- This is my home.

01:03:26.448 --> 01:03:28.931
- You know what I mean.

01:03:31.344 --> 01:03:33.793
- I've been nothing
but a friend to everybody here.

01:03:34.965 --> 01:03:36.344
If somebody wants me to leave,

01:03:36.448 --> 01:03:38.034
you can tell them
to come make me.

01:03:38.137 --> 01:03:41.655
- Pretty silly thing to say
on a reservation.

01:03:43.034 --> 01:03:44.344
I don't ask much,

01:03:44.448 --> 01:03:47.068
but I'm asking you this.

01:03:47.172 --> 01:03:50.206
Go home.

01:03:50.310 --> 01:03:53.517
Take care of my granddaughter.

01:03:53.620 --> 01:03:56.413
Be good to that boy.

01:03:56.517 --> 01:04:00.344
Until they find a cure
for human nature,

01:04:00.448 --> 01:04:03.275
a man must stand
with his people.

01:04:06.655 --> 01:04:10.241
And we are not your people.

01:04:10.344 --> 01:04:13.275
[somber music]

01:04:13.379 --> 01:04:18.793
♪

01:04:25.517 --> 01:04:28.517
- Hey.
Hey, Jimmy!

01:04:28.620 --> 01:04:30.275
Let's go.
You're late.

01:04:30.379 --> 01:04:31.793
Let's go. You're late.

01:04:32.896 --> 01:04:35.620
You know how to ride a horse?
- Uh...

01:04:35.724 --> 01:04:38.655
- Figures. Come here.
Give me your shit.

01:04:38.758 --> 01:04:40.655
Let's go.
That there is Ron.

01:04:40.758 --> 01:04:42.034
You do whatever the hell
he asks you to do.

01:04:42.827 --> 01:04:46.344
Come on, get on.
Get on the horse.

01:04:46.448 --> 01:04:46.827
- I don't--

01:04:49.241 --> 01:04:49.931
- Get on the horse, Jimmy.

01:04:54.413 --> 01:04:57.482
Pull the reins to stop.
Kick him in the belly to go.

01:04:57.586 --> 01:04:58.862
All right, let's move.

01:05:07.655 --> 01:05:09.172
- Both in one night?

01:05:10.379 --> 01:05:13.724
- Everyone's forgotten
who runs this valley.

01:05:14.758 --> 01:05:16.827
- So this is how you
remind them?

01:05:17.862 --> 01:05:18.379
This is not the way
to remind them. It's a--

01:05:18.482 --> 01:05:21.241
It's a bad idea.

01:05:21.344 --> 01:05:23.275
- We don't choose the way,
little brother.

01:05:24.586 --> 01:05:27.965
[helicopter powering up]

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:53.103
[Pucifer's "Tumbleweed"]

01:05:53.206 --> 01:06:00.103
♪

01:06:03.965 --> 01:06:06.827
- Dad,
I'm the fastest runner.

01:06:06.931 --> 01:06:09.000
I'm bucking.
I'm bucking.

01:06:10.551 --> 01:06:12.586
And he falls.

01:06:12.689 --> 01:06:14.034
[thud]
[laughs]

